issue.title: Security Concern: Remove telnetlib for Improved Security
issue.body:
### Did you follow the steps from https://github.com/napalm-automation/napalm#faq
(Place an "x" between the square brackets where applicable)

- [X] Yes
- [] No

**Issue Description**:
I recently ran a security scan on the Napalm library, and it identified a potential security vulnerability related to the use of the `telnetlib` library within `napalm/ios/ios.py` (full path: [napalm/ios/ios.py](https://github.com/napalm-automation/napalm/blob/develop/napalm/ios/ios.py)). Telnet is a well-known insecure protocol, and its use in network automation can pose security risks. The security scan identified this as a high-severity issue, and it's recommended to remove this library if applicable. 

**Suggested Action**:
I propose that we consider removing the use of `telnetlib` from the Napalm library to enhance security. This can help prevent potential security vulnerabilities associated with the Telnet protocol.

**Reasoning**:
- Telnet is inherently insecure and transmits data in clear text, making it vulnerable to eavesdropping and unauthorized access.
- Modern network automation and configuration management should prioritize secure protocols like SSH or NETCONF.
- Security best practices recommend removing or deprecating insecure components.

**Steps to Reproduce (if applicable)**:
N/A

**Additional Information**:
I understand that this change may require some code adjustments and possibly affect compatibility with certain devices. However, the security and privacy of network management should be a top priority. I'm willing to contribute to this change or collaborate with others to make this transition as smooth as possible.

**Related Links**:
- [Bandit Security Issue](https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/1.7.5/blacklists/blacklist_imports.html#b401-import-telnetlib)
- [CWE-319 - Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)

**Assignees**:
@code-with-ryan

I would ask to be assigned to become more acclimated with the codebase and to contribute, if possible. I understand if the creators would like to leverage someone with more familiarity, however. 

Your assistance in addressing this security concern is highly appreciated. Let's work together to improve the security of the Napalm library for all users.

Best,

--Ryan

comment.body:
@code-with-ryan Yes, telnet is in cleartext. End-users should not use it in cases where it is inappropriate for their security policies.

Unfortunately, there are a meaningful number of field devices that still only support telnet and consequently it is still needed.

issue.title: VLAN getters
issue.body:
Following on from a discussion in NTC slack. Adding VLAN getters would be a nice addition IMO.
@ktbyers mentioned that he is open to at least a discussion on adding VLAN getters.

Some closed issues in this topic from the past 
https://github.com/napalm-automation/napalm/issues/571
https://github.com/napalm-automation/napalm-base/issues/252

I need this functionality for mainly Junos and Cumulus drivers so can focus my energy there if there is some agreement to move forward.

CC @jobec

comment.body:
This doesn't seem to have been implemented as far as I can tell - get_vlans() only outputs what interfaces permit what vlans to pass over them, not whether they are in access or trunk mode.

@mirceaulinic was this going to be implemented in the main napalm repo or is the above PR still needing work?
